          "body": "Unlike virtually every other country in the world, the United States taxes its citizens on worldwide income — regardless of where they live. This is citizenship-based taxation, and it means that even a US citizen who has lived in Singapore for twenty years and holds no US assets must still file an annual return with the IRS.\n\nBeyond income tax, US persons are required to file an FBAR (FinCEN Form 114) if aggregate foreign account balances exceed $10,000 at any point during the year. They must also comply with FATCA (Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act), which requires foreign financial institutions to report accounts held by US persons to the IRS — making it increasingly difficult to hold foreign accounts without US disclosure.\n\nFor HNWIs, the structural implication is significant: the US passport comes with a permanent tax obligation. This is why some ultra-high-net-worth Americans choose to renounce citizenship — but renunciation itself triggers the Exit Tax under the HEART Act (Heroes Earnings Assistance and Relief Tax Act of 2008), which treats all worldwide assets as sold at fair market value on the day of expatriation. Capital gains tax applies to that deemed sale.\n\nPlanning for this Exit Tax is a discipline in itself — and one of the most complex areas of international tax law."
