          "text": "In 2007 a client called Victor from Geneva.\n\nThe client was a Swiss-educated Korean industrialist, third-generation, who had moved his family to Singapore five years earlier. He had a question. His Swiss private bank had just sent him a letter. The letter asked him to confirm whether he was a US person under FATCA — which did not yet exist in 2007, but whose precursor legislation was already moving through the US Senate.\n\n\"What does this mean?\" the client asked.\n\n\"It means the US is going to change everything,\" Victor said.\n\nHe had read about the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act proposal. He had read it twice, carefully, in the National Library on Victoria Street on a Saturday morning. His margin notes ran three pages.\n\nThe client said, \"But I'm Korean, not American.\"\n\n\"It doesn't matter. Your bank is American-adjacent. Any bank that touches the US financial system will comply. That's every serious bank in the world.\"\n\nThere was a long silence.\n\n\"So what do I do?\"\n\nVictor said, \"You don't hide. You structure.\"\n\nThat phrase — you don't hide, you structure — became the sentence Victor used more than any other over the next twenty years."
