          "body": "Global corporate structure design must simultaneously achieve four objectives: tax efficiency, asset protection, business scalability, and succession ease. In practice these four often conflict. Maximizing tax efficiency can produce structures so complex they become operationally unwieldy. Maximizing asset protection through trust structures can limit the founder's operational control. The key is calibrating the right balance for the family's specific situation.\n\nThe basic principles: First, separate business operating companies from asset-holding companies. The operating company takes operational risk; the holding company protects accumulated wealth from business failure. Second, domicile the holding company in a jurisdiction with a strong DTT network, political stability, and a clear legal framework for ownership disputes. Singapore, the UK (historically), the Netherlands, Luxembourg, and Ireland are the most commonly used. Third, ensure the structure reflects genuine economic substance — real employees, real management decisions, real business activity in the holding jurisdiction. Post-BEPS (OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting rules), hollow shell structures with no economic substance face aggressive challenge.\n\nFor PE-backed exits and cross-border M&A, the typical structure is a Cayman Islands holding company at the apex, with operating subsidiaries in the relevant jurisdictions below. The Cayman structure is chosen because: Cayman has no corporation tax, no capital gains tax, no withholding tax, and broad recognition in US and UK legal systems. PE firms are operationally familiar with Cayman structures and can acquire into them cleanly."
