          "body": "The cap table is not merely an accounting document. It is the legal blueprint that determines who receives how much when the business exits. A poorly designed cap table at founding can produce millions in unnecessary tax on exit and create barriers to investment or M&A transactions.\n\nFounders' shares should ideally be issued at nominal value at inception, with vesting schedules that protect the company from departing founders. If a co-founder departs early, their unvested shares should return to the pool — protecting the remaining founders' and investors' equity value.\n\nFor UK-based founders, SEIS (Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme) and EIS (Enterprise Investment Scheme) relief provides up to 50% income tax relief on early-stage investments and CGT exemption on qualifying disposals. These schemes incentivize early institutional investment into UK startups and are genuinely attractive mechanisms — the reliefs are real and well-established in UK practice.\n\nEmployee Share Option Plans (ESOP or EMI — Enterprise Management Incentives in the UK) are essential for talent retention. UK EMI options carry significant tax advantages: options can be granted with exercise prices below market value, and on exercise, gains above the exercise price are taxed as capital gains (24% from 2024) rather than income (45%). The UK's EMI scheme is widely regarded as one of the most employee-friendly option schemes globally, alongside Singapore's ESOP equivalents.\n\nWhen an overseas acquisition is anticipated, restructuring the holding company into a Cayman entity 12–24 months before the expected transaction is standard practice. US PE acquirers and London-listed SPACs both expect Cayman or Delaware holding structures."
