          "body": "M&A exit produces a short-period cash event of significant scale. Pre-event tax structuring is the highest-value activity a HNWI advisor can perform.\n\nThe first strategy is residency change. If the founder moves to a Singapore tax residency before the transaction closes, and the share sale is structured as a Singapore-sourced capital gain (sale of Singapore company shares or Cayman holding company shares held through Singapore SFO), Singapore's zero capital gains tax applies. The gain on a USD 50 million business exit could save USD 8–12 million in tax compared with a UK 24% CGT outcome — covering many years of Singapore residency costs.\n\nThe second strategy is holding company interposition. Where a Cayman or Singapore holding company sits between the founder and the operating company at least 12–24 months prior to sale, the acquirer can acquire the holding company shares. If the holding company is a Singapore entity held through the SFO, Section 13O/13U exemption may apply to the disposition proceeds.\n\nThe third strategy is rollover and deferral. In PE deals, taking a portion of the consideration as rolled equity in the acquiring PE vehicle defers the tax event on that portion until the PE vehicle's own exit. If the founder's residency is Singapore at that later exit, the deferred gain also benefits from zero CGT.\n\nTiming precision matters. UK CGT is triggered at the point of legally binding exchange of contracts (not completion). If the founder moves to Singapore before exchange — not just before completion — the UK tax position on the deferred element changes materially. Legal and tax advisors must be aligned on the exact timing sequence."
