          "type": "deep",
          "title": "15.2 Dynasty Trust: Wealth Protection Across Generations",
          "body": "A Dynasty Trust is designed to persist indefinitely. While ordinary trusts are limited to a specific period or the beneficiary's lifetime, a Dynasty Trust continues as long as trust law permits. Cayman, BVI, and Jersey all permit trusts that can last in perpetuity — or for the maximum period allowed by law, which in many jurisdictions is now unlimited.\n\nThe Dynasty Trust's purpose: to keep family wealth together across multiple generations, insulated from the risks each generation individually faces — business failure, divorce, creditor claims, profligate spending, and fragmentation through inheritance. Rather than distributing capital to each child who reaches adulthood (which disperses wealth rapidly through splitting), the Dynasty Trust continues to own and manage the wealth institutionally, distributing income and making capital distributions based on the trustee's discretion guided by the trust deed.\n\nFor UK-origin HNWIs, UK inheritance tax (IHT) — charged at 40% on estates above GBP 325,000 — is the primary motivation for trust planning. A properly established offshore discretionary trust, with assets transferred to the trust while the settlor is genuinely non-UK domiciled, can place those assets outside the UK IHT net. Assets in the trust belong to the trust, not the individual — on death, they do not form part of the estate for IHT purposes.\n\nThe timing caveat: UK IHT applies to UK-domiciled individuals' worldwide assets. Under the post-2025 rules (which replaced the non-dom/domicile framework), UK residents are generally UK-domiciled after 15+ years of UK residence. The IHT exposure must be addressed — through trust structuring — before that threshold is crossed, not after."
