          "text": "The message came at two in the morning.\n\nIt was Seong-jun.\n\n'Victor. Director Choi passed away.'\n\nVictor stared at the screen for a long time. Outside the Singapore window, the streetlights of Orchard Road swayed in the rain. Director Choi. Age 91.\n\nHe got up from the bed and went out onto the terrace. He did not avoid the rain. He simply stood.\n\nThere was something Director Choi had never said to Victor directly. But Victor had always known it.\n\nThe director had never given advice. He had never said, 'Do this,' or 'Do not do that.' He had only ever asked questions.\n\n'Victor-ssi, what do you think is the most important thing?' A question asked in Yeongdo, when Victor was twelve. He had answered, 'Money.' The director had nodded. Not disagreeing. Not agreeing. Just listening.\n\nIn Singapore at 42, Victor now had a different answer. Not money. Structure. Not structure alone. People. Not just people. Continuity.\n\nHe stood in the rain on the terrace for a long time.\n\nIn the morning he wrote a one-paragraph addition to his family constitution document.\n\n'The purpose of this family's wealth is not to be preserved. The purpose is to be used — for the family, for people the family cares about, and for the next generation that the family hopes will do better than the one before.'"
