          "body": "The Family Council is a formal body responsible for communication, decision-making, and education among family members. Just as a board of directors governs a corporation, the Family Council governs the family.\n\nA standard three-level structure: first, the Family Assembly — all family members (including spouses and adult children from all branches), meeting annually. The Assembly is the broadest consultative body — updates on family wealth, educational sessions, and high-level direction-setting. Second, the Family Council — a smaller elected or appointed body of 5–9 members representing the key family branches. The Council meets quarterly, makes operational decisions, oversees the family office, and monitors compliance with the Family Charter. Third, the Investment Committee — professional sub-committee of the Council, typically comprising family members with financial backgrounds plus independent external advisors. Meets monthly to review investment performance, risk, and strategic allocation.\n\nFor UK-origin HNWI families with assets in Singapore, the Middle East, and multiple countries, the Family Council is the governance mechanism that prevents the family from falling apart across generations. Without it, each branch of the family effectively manages separately — the family office's economies of scale and institutional management capabilities erode, and the dynasty trust's integrated purpose is undermined.\n\nSuccessful Family Councils require: clear written mandates, regular meeting schedules (with minutes and formal records), term limits for Council positions, structured onboarding for next-generation members who reach adulthood, and an external family governance advisor who observes Council meetings and provides independent feedback."
