          "body": "The sustainability of a family foundation is determined by the formula: return rate > expenditure rate. This is the core of all long-term institutional management.\n\nScenario 1 (Conservative): Initial capital GBP 10 million. Annual average return 5%. Annual expenditure 3%. Net annual growth: 2%. After 100 years, the real purchasing-power-adjusted value of the foundation approximately doubles — the foundation survives and grows modestly.\n\nScenario 2 (Balanced): Initial capital GBP 10 million. Annual average return 7%. Annual expenditure 4%. Net annual growth: 3%. After 100 years, the foundation grows to approximately GBP 190 million in nominal terms.\n\nScenario 3 (Ambitious): Initial capital GBP 10 million. Annual average return 9%. Annual expenditure 5%. Net annual growth: 4%. After 100 years, nominal value exceeds GBP 500 million. This is the Yale endowment trajectory — achievable with a high-conviction illiquidity-heavy portfolio.\n\nThe discipline: the expenditure rate must be legally fixed and institutionally enforced. When families encounter financial pressure — a generation's business failure, a divorce settlement, a health crisis — the temptation to draw down the foundation's capital is structural. The solution is legal: a trust deed or foundation charter that explicitly prohibits capital drawdown below a specified floor, enforced by the trustee or board independently of family control.\n\nFor UK-origin foundations, HMRC requires that UK-registered charities spend or commit to spend a minimum percentage of their investment income annually (the 'expenditure test'). This creates a policy floor for the expenditure rate — the foundation cannot simply accumulate without deploying. Understanding and planning around this requirement is part of the UK charity's annual compliance cycle."
