          "body": "Norway's GPFG (Government Pension Fund Global), Singapore's GIC and Temasek, and Abu Dhabi's ADIA are institutions designed to preserve and grow national assets permanently. Applying their management philosophy at the family level is the most ambitious form of HNWI wealth management.\n\nThe core principle of sovereign wealth management: separate ownership from management. The Norwegian government owns the GPFG but does not manage it — Norges Bank Investment Management (NBIM) manages it at arm's length. The governance boundary is explicit: politicians cannot direct individual investment decisions. The same principle applies to the family sovereign wealth structure: the family (through the Family Council and the Dynasty Trust) owns the capital, but the Family Office CEO and Investment Committee manage it independently, subject to the Investment Policy Statement rather than ad hoc family direction.\n\nThe Investment Policy Statement (IPS) is the governing document — equivalent to a sovereign wealth fund's mandate. It specifies: long-term return objective (real return above inflation, typically 4–5% net); asset allocation target ranges; liquidity requirements; ESG and impact investing constraints; leverage limitations; counterparty concentration limits; and review and amendment process. The IPS is reviewed annually and amended only by the Family Council — the investment team executes within it without requiring Council approval for individual transactions.\n\nFor UK-origin families at the scale of a 100-year dynasty trust, the IPS becomes the document that outlasts any individual — it contains the family's capital management philosophy in written, reviewable, enforceable form. 'What would the founder have decided' becomes a question answered by the IPS, not by memory or interpretation."
