          "body": "A family that endures 100 years does not treat crises as exceptions. Crises are inevitable — financial collapse, wars, pandemics, regime changes, technological revolutions. The question is not whether a crisis will come but what kind of crisis, and how the structure responds.\n\nThe resilience framework has four layers. First: financial resilience — maintaining a minimum 12 months of family living expenses plus the liquidity required for all committed capital calls in genuinely liquid assets at all times. This is the cash reserve requirement that no investment pressure can override. Second: structural resilience — the trust structure, the SFO's Section 13O status, the corporate entities, and the bank relationships all have documented contingency plans. What happens if Singapore changes its family office regime? (Shift to Dubai or Switzerland.) What happens if the primary private bank fails? (Three custodians, not one.)\n\nThird: geographic resilience — the family has genuine residency options in at least three jurisdictions, and the passports to exercise them. Fourth: succession resilience — if the family office CEO dies or becomes incapacitated tomorrow, the Investment Committee can operate continuously. The Investment Policy Statement is the mandate; the committee is the governance; the legal structures are in place. No single person's absence should interrupt capital management for more than 30 days.\n\nFor UK-origin families, the specific crisis to model is a sudden change in UK tax law that retroactively affects non-resident status or IHT exposure. The UK has done this before — the 2017 changes to non-dom rules for long-term UK residents, and the 2025 abolition of non-dom status, were both material changes with relatively short notice. The resilience question: if the UK announced a 90-day window to restructure before a new regime applied, what would you do? Having the answer in advance is worth the cost of the planning."
