          "body": "The Family Constitution is the family's permanent code. Not just the living generation — descendants not yet born will read this document decades from now and make decisions based on it. It must therefore contain enduring principles rather than conditions of a specific era.\n\nCore sections: Part 1 — Foundation. The family's origins, the founding generation's values, and the purpose of accumulated wealth ('what the wealth is for'). Part 2 — Governance. The structure and powers of the Family Assembly, Family Council, and Investment Committee. Voting procedures, quorum, term limits, and amendment processes. Part 3 — Wealth Management. The Investment Policy Statement summary, asset allocation philosophy, the Family Bank framework, and the conditions under which capital can be deployed for family members' entrepreneurial ventures. Part 4 — Succession. The next-generation education requirements, the re-entry criteria for the family office, and the authority transfer milestones. Part 5 — Philanthropy. The family's giving philosophy, the foundation's mandate, and the social impact investment framework. Part 6 — Dispute Resolution. The process for resolving family disagreements — beginning with internal mediation, proceeding to independent arbitration before any recourse to litigation.\n\nThe constitution should be reviewed and if necessary amended every five years by the Family Council, with a two-thirds majority required for any amendment to the foundational sections. The review process itself — convening the family, discussing whether the principles still reflect the family's values, making deliberate choices about what to change — is as valuable as the document.\n\nFor UK-origin families now distributed across Singapore, Australia, Dubai, and Europe, the Family Constitution is the common framework that holds the family together across jurisdictions where different laws, different tax systems, and different cultural norms would otherwise pull them apart."
